Index construction begins by assigning a momentum score to the 2,000 largest constituents by market cap in the NASDAQ US Benchmark index. The score is based on upward price movements of the security compared to the benchmark and other eligible securities within the universe. The top 30 highest momentum-scoring stocks in the consumer discretionary sector are then chosen for the index with higher scoring securities receiving greater weight. The portfolio tilts small, with a growth bias and somewhat higher risk. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. Prior to August 28, 2023, the fund traded under the name Invesco DWA Consumer Cyclicals Momentum ETF.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the Dorsey Wright® Consumer Cyclicals Technical Leaders Index (the "underlying index"). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of at least 30 securities of companies in the consumer discretionary (or cyclicals) sector that have powerful relative strength or "momentum" characteristics.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Real Estate ETF
merged_description: This fund offers unique exposure to the U.S. real estate sector by applying an equal-weighting methodology to companies within the S&P 500® Real Estate Index. By equally weighting its constituents, the fund diminishes the concentration risk typically found in market-cap weighted approaches and provides a more balanced representation across eligible large-cap real estate stocks. Its portfolio, composed of S&P 500 companies classified under the GICS real estate sector, primarily includes equity REITs and real estate management and development firms, while specifically excluding mortgage REITs. The fund generally invests at least 90% of its assets in the securities that make up its underlying index, offering a distinct, equal-weighted alternative for large-cap real estate investment.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Real Estate Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the real estate sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_etfcom: RSPR is the first equal-weighted ETF in the US real estate segment. Equal-weighting shrinks the footprint of the largest REITs in the portfolio, but the funds S&P 500 universe excludes small-caps, which would otherwise tilt the portfolio much smaller. The fund includes a small portion of non-REIT real estate management and development companies, while mortgage REITs are out of bounds. In all, RSPR offers a concentrated, equal-weight alternative in a space dominated by cap-weighted funds. Through September 2016, RSPR had failed to attract any investor interest. This changed somewhat due to an unusual arrangement with sister fund RSPF, which needed to divest itself of REITs to comply with a GICS classification change. RSPF provided AUM in the form of REITs to RSPR in return for its shares, which were then distributed to RSPF shareholders as of Sep. 16, 2016, thus providing a modest but critical boost to RSPRs AUM. Prior to June 7, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker EWRE.
description_yahoo: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Real Estate Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the real estate sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard ("GICS").

name: The Materials Select Sector SPDR Fund
merged_description: This investment fund aims to mirror the performance, before expenses, of an index representing the materials sector within the S&P 500. Employing a replication strategy, it invests substantially all (at least 95%) of its assets in the index's constituent securities, providing precise exposure to U.S. companies primarily involved in industries such as chemicals, metals and mining, paper and forest products, containers and packaging, and construction materials. Sourced exclusively from the S&P 500's materials components, the underlying index is weighted by free-float market capitalization, subject to capping constraints and quarterly rebalancing, which results in a portfolio favouring large-cap stocks. This targeted approach leads to significant concentration, allowing investors to make focused strategic or tactical allocations specifically within the basic materials industry.
description_original: The Materials Select Sector SPDR Fund seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of the Materials Select Sector Index (the “Index”).The Index seeks to provide an effective representation of the materials sector of the S&P 500 Index.Seeks to provide precise exposure to companies in the chemical; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction material industries.Allows investors to take strategic or tactical positions at a more targeted level than traditional style based investing.
description_etfcom:
XLB tracks a market-cap-weighted index of US basic materials companies. The fund includes only the materials components of the S&P 500.

XLB invests in basic materials companies from the S&P 500, these would include companies in the chemicals, metals and mining, paper and forest products, containers and packaging, and construction materials industry. Its limited selection universe means it is heavily concentrated, and individual holdings must be taken into consideration before investing in this fund. Not surprisingly, XLB favors large-caps. Components of the index are all picked by the index committee, and weighed by free-float market capitalization, subject to a cap to ensure diversification requirements. Index rebalancing occurs quarterly.
description_yahoo: In seeking to track the performance of the index, the fund employs a replication strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 95%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index includes securities of companies from the following industries: chemicals; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction materials. The fund is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of publicly traded equity securities of companies in the Materials Select Sector Index. In seeking to track the performance of the index, the fund employs a replication strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 95%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index includes securities of companies from the following industries: chemicals; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction materials. The fund is non-diversified.

name: VanEck Social Sentiment ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund aims to capture positive investor sentiment by tracking an index of U.S. large- and mid-cap stocks exhibiting significant favorable discussion online. Employing a rules-based quantitative methodology, it analyzes diverse sources such as social media, news articles, and blog posts to identify companies generating the most positive insights and buzz. The fund invests primarily (at least 80% of assets) in the index components, resulting in a concentrated, non-diversified portfolio typically holding around 75 stocks selected based on this sentiment analysis. Holdings are weighted using a proprietary scoring model, with individual stock weights capped at 3%, and the index is reconstituted and rebalanced monthly to reflect current sentiment trends.
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is comprised of common stocks of U.S. companies selected by a rules-based quantitative methodology developed by the index Provider, which is designed to identify the U.S. common stocks with the most "positive insights" collected from online sources including social media, news articles, blog posts and other alternative datasets. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom: BUZZ seeks to reflect the investor sentiment online. It looks for investment-related mentions of large- and midcap US-listed firms in relevant online sources including social media, news articles and blog posts. Using a proprietary algorithm, eligible companies that meet certain market-cap and liquidity requirements are scored and ranked by insight, which indicates the degree of positive sentiment and breadth of discussion on the internet. Based on this scoring process, BUZZ curates a concentrated portfolio of 75 firms with the most positive investor sentiment. Holdings are weighted using a proprietary scoring model, with single constituent weights capped at 3%. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced monthly.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track as closely as possible, before fees and expenses, the price and yield performance of the BUZZ NextGen AI US Sentiment Leaders Index. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is comprised of common stocks of U.S. companies selected by a rules-based quantitative methodology developed by the index Provider, which is designed to identify the U.S. common stocks with the most "positive insights" collected from online sources including social media, news articles, blog posts and other alternative datasets. The fund is non-diversified.

name: First Trust US Equity Opportunities UCITS ETF
merged_description: This investment fund aims to replicate the performance of an index focused on recent U.S. initial public offerings (IPOs). The index comprises the 100 largest and typically most liquid U.S. companies that have recently gone public, including spin-offs and equity carve-outs. Adhering to its index, the fund normally invests at least 90% of its assets in these securities. A key feature is its specific holding period: eligible stocks are typically acquired shortly after listing and held for approximately their first 1,000 trading days, equating to roughly four years. The portfolio is market-capitalization weighted, incorporates a 10% cap on individual security weights, and is classified as non-diversified. Notably, constituent companies remain included even if they merge with or are acquired by a mature company during this holding period.
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks that comprise the index. The index seeks to measure the performance of equity securities of the 100 typically largest and most liquid initial public offerings ("IPOs") (including spin-offs and equity carve-outs) of U.S. companies. It is non-diversified.
description_etfcom:
FPX tracks a market-cap-weighted index of the 100 largest US IPOs over the first 1,000 trading days for each stock.

FPX holds positions in the 100 largest, and typically most liquid, US firms with recent IPOs. Eligible stocks are purchased after the close on the 6th trading day and sold on the 1000th, for a holding period of roughly 4 years. The fund applies further quantitative screens in addition to the usual de minimis size and liquidity requirements, but these are fairly relaxed. It is also market cap-weighted with a capping scheme of 10% for each individual security. See sibling funds FPXE and FPXI for Europe and broad international exposure, respectively, using the same methodology. Prior to December 14, 2016, the fund traded with the name First Trust US IPO Index ETF, however its name change bore no impact to FPXs investment strategy. One caveat worth noting: In the case of an index constituent merging with or being acquired by a mature company, the resulting entity will remain included in the index.
description_yahoo: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index seeks to measure the performance of equity securities of the 100 typically largest and most liquid initial public offerings ("IPOs") (including spin-offs and equity carve-outs) of U.S. companies. It is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an equity index called the IPOX®-100 U.S. Index. The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index seeks to measure the performance of equity securities of the 100 typically largest and most liquid initial public offerings ("IPOs") (including spin-offs and equity carve-outs) of U.S. companies. It is non-diversified.

name: John Hancock Multifactor Media and Communications ETF
merged_description: This investment fund primarily allocates at least 80% of its net assets, including any borrowed funds, to mirror the holdings of its underlying index. The index is constructed from U.S. companies within the media and communications sector, targeting securities with market capitalizations larger than the 1001st largest U.S. company during index reconstitution periods. Characterized as non-diversified, the fund concentrates its investments within this specific market segment.
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus any borrowings for investment purposes) in securities that compose the fund's index. The index is designed to comprise securities in the media and communications sector within the U.S. Universe whose market capitalizations are larger than that of the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution. It is non-diversified.

name: iShares MSCI Global Energy Producers ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund seeks to track an index comprising global equity securities of companies primarily engaged in energy exploration and production, covering both developed and emerging markets. Generally investing at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of its underlying index or in investments with substantially identical economic characteristics, the fund draws from an all-cap universe. It selects companies involved in oil and gas exploration and production, as well as coal and consumable fuel production and mining, while excluding firms whose primary business involves downstream activities or alternative fuels. However, due to significant holdings in large Integrated Oil & Gas companies, the fund provides broad exposure to global energy producers rather than being purely concentrated on the exploration and production segment. This fund is non-diversified, and its underlying index is reviewed quarterly.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index measures the combined performance of equity securities of companies in both developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom:
FILL tracks an index of companies in developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production.

FILL offers exposure to the global Oil & Gas Exploration and Production (E&P) segment. It will invest in atleast 40% of its assets in issuers and businesses in developed and emerging markets. The fund covers the all cap exposure of its parent index MSCI ACWI Investable Market Index, then selects firms primarily engaged in the exploration and production of oil and gas or in the production and mining of coal and other consumable fuels related to the generation of energy as classified by GICS. It excludes firms whose majority of revenues are on downstream and alternative fuels business. However, FILL is not pure-play on Oil and Gas E&P space as it invests heavily into the Integrated Oil & Gas sector with companies like Exxon Mobil, BP and Chevron. Index constituents are reviewed quarterly.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI ACWI Select Energy Producers Investable Market Index (IMI). The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index measures the combined performance of equity securities of companies in both developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production. The fund is non-diversified.

name: John Hancock Multifactor Energy ETF
merged_description: Focused on the U.S. energy sector, this non-diversified fund employs a multifactor strategy, investing at least 80% of its net assets, plus any borrowings, in securities composing its underlying index. The index targets U.S. energy companies whose market capitalizations place them above the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution, effectively concentrating on larger firms within the sector while utilizing multiple factors for security selection and weighting.
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus any borrowings for investment purposes) in securities that compose the fund's index. The index is designed to comprise securities in the energy sector within the U.S. Universe whose market capitalizations are larger than that of the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Pacer Industrials and Logistics ETF
merged_description: This passively managed, rules-based exchange-traded fund tracks an index of globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts, offering exposure to industrials and logistics companies essential to global supply chain operations. The underlying index includes firms meeting size and liquidity criteria that derive at least 50% of their revenue from relevant activities such as transportation services (freight, trucking, couriers), supply chain-related software or hardware (logistics software, robotics), or associated consultation services. Holdings are weighted by market capitalization, with constraints including a 10% cap on individual securities and a 45% limit on the aggregate weight of constituents exceeding 4.5% allocation. This non-diversified fund reconstitutes and rebalances its index annually.
description_original: A rules-based exchange traded fund (ETF) that aims to offer investors exposure to globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts involved in the support and functioning of global distribution supply chains.
description_etfcom: SHPP is passively managed to invest in globally listed stocks and depositary receipts of industrials and logistics companies. The fund includes firms that derive at least 50% of their revenue from: (i) transportation, such as air, ocean, and rail freight, trucking, and other courier services, (ii) software, including transportation management services and logistics software, (iii) hardware, such as robotics and forklifts, or (iv) consultation services that support global supply chains. The selection process starts with companies that meet size and liquidity criteria. Eligible firms are then screened based on descriptions of a companys business activities in regulatory filings, analyst reports, website, and industry-specific trade publications. Holdings are weighted by market-cap, subject to a 10% single security capping. In addition, the aggregate weight of constituents with over 4.5% allocation is capped at 45%. The index reconstitutes and rebalances annually.
description_yahoo: The fund employs a “passive management” (or indexing) investment approach designed to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the index. The index consists of globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts of industrials and logistics companies. The fund is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Pacer Global Supply Chain Infrastructure Index. The fund employs a “passive management” (or indexing) investment approach designed to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the index. The index consists of globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts of industrials and logistics companies. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Defiance Nasdaq Junior Biotechnology ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the NASDAQ Junior Biotechnology Index. This rules-based index comprises U.S.-listed small-capitalization ("junior") biotechnology firms screened from the larger NASDAQ Biotechnology Index. The fund generally utilizes a replication strategy, aiming to hold all index constituents in approximately the same proportions as the index itself. It is important to note that this fund is considered non-diversified.
description_original: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the NASDAQ Junior Biotechnology Index. The index is a rules-based index that consists of a portfolio of the stock of U.S.-listed small capitalization ("junior") companies screened from the universe of the NASDAQ Biotechnology Index. The fund will generally use a "replication" strategy to achieve its investment objective, meaning it will generally invest in all of the component securities of the index in the same approximate proportions as in the index. The fund is non-diversified.
description_yahoo:
The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the NASDAQ Junior Biotechnology Index.
 The index is a rules-based index that consists of a portfolio of the stock of U.S.-listed small capitalization ("junior") companies screened from the universe of the NASDAQ Biotechnology Index. The fund will generally use a "replication" strategy to achieve its investment objective, meaning it will generally invest in all of the component securities of the index in the same approximate proportions as in the index. The fund is non-diversified.

name: SPDR MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned ETF
merged_description: This non-diversified fund tracks an index of US large- and mid-cap stocks, specifically selected and weighted to align with the Paris Agreement's climate goals and facilitate a transition to a low-carbon economy. The underlying index methodology exceeds the minimum standards for an EU Paris-Aligned Benchmark and incorporates recommendations from the Taskforce on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD). It systematically screens out companies involved in controversial sectors like thermal coal, oil and gas, and tobacco, as well as those with severe ESG or environmental issues. An optimization process then targets significant reductions in greenhouse gas intensity and climate-related risks (both physical and transition), while simultaneously increasing exposure to sustainable investment opportunities and green revenues. While pursuing these climate objectives, the strategy aims to maintain sector exposures broadly similar to the parent US market index, using a semi-annual rebalancing approach, making it potentially suitable for investors implementing net-zero strategies.
description_original: NZUS seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned Index (“the Index”)Seeks to track an index designed to reduce exposure to the physical and transition risks of climate change and increase target exposure to sustainable investment opportunities by incorporating the recommendations of the Taskforce on Climate Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD) and minimum requirements of the EU Paris Aligned BenchmarkMay be considered by investors seeking to implement net-zero strategies and address climate change in a holistic way
description_etfcom:
NZUS tracks a tier-weighted index of large- and mid-cap US stocks selected and weighted based on ESG criteria that are compatible with the Paris Climate Agreement and carbon reduction goals.

NZUS takes a climate approach to investing in the US large- and mid-cap space by tracking an index geared toward a low-carbon economy transition. The index initially screens out stocks from the MSCI USA Index, that are involved in controversial weapons, tobacco, thermal coal mining, oil and gas, and power generation, as well as severe ESG controversies and environmental issues. The portfolio selection and weighting utilize an optimization process that minimizes exposure to physical and transition risks of climate change while providing exposure to sustainable investment opportunities. Optimization constraints include greenhouse gas intensity reduction, low carbon transition score, climate value-at-risk, green revenue, and fossil fuels-based revenue. The index also uses an optimizer to maintain the sector weighting in the parent index. NZUS uses a sampling strategy to track its index, which is rebalanced semi-annually.
description_yahoo: The fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index is designed to exceed the minimum standards for a “Paris-Aligned Benchmark” under the EU BMR. The fund is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned Index. The fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index is designed to exceed the minimum standards for a “Paris-Aligned Benchmark” under the EU BMR. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Putnam ESG Ultra Short ETF
merged_description: This fixed-income fund seeks high current income consistent with capital preservation and liquidity by investing in a diversified portfolio of short-duration, investment-grade securities. Holdings primarily consist of money market instruments and other fixed-income securities, including U.S. dollar-denominated foreign, government, and corporate debt, while maintaining an overall portfolio duration of one year or less and individual security maturities under four years. A core characteristic is its focus on issuers meeting stringent environmental, social, and governance (ESG) standards, which are assessed on a sector-specific basis using a proprietary materiality map; only the highest-rated issuers are considered following fundamental analysis, with evaluation methods adapted for complex asset types like securitized and sovereign debt.
description_original: The fund invests in a diversified short duration portfolio of fixed-income securities comprised of investment-grade money market and other fixed-income securities, including U.S. dollar-denominated foreign securities of these types, with a focus on companies or issuers that Putnam Management, the fund’s investment manager, believes meet relevant environmental, social or governance (“ESG”) criteria on a sector-specific basis (“ESG criteria”).
description_etfcom: PULT invests in short-term, investment grade fixed income securities from around the world that meet ESG standards on a sector-specific basis. The fund maintains a portfolio duration of no more than one year and a maturity of four years or less. It may include government and corporate debt securities. The fund assesses fundamentals that include the industry, location, strategic position, and key relationships. Securities are assigned an ESG rating, and only the highest-rated ones are considered. To identify relevant ESG criteria on a sector-specific basis, the fund uses an internally developed materiality map that determines which criteria are deemed important for a given sector. For example, securitized debt securities are broadly evaluated due to various asset types, counterparties, complex market structures, and scarce ESG data. Sovereign debt is evaluated using quantitative models and research, as better ESG scores may influence a countrys credit risk and borrowing costs.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks as high a rate of current income as Franklin Advisers, Inc. (Franklin Advisers) believes is consistent with preservation of capital and maintenance of liquidity. The fund invests in a diversified short duration portfolio of fixed-income securities comprised of investment-grade money market and other fixed-income securities, including U.S. dollar-denominated foreign securities of these types, with a focus on companies or issuers that Putnam Management, the fund’s investment manager, believes meet relevant environmental, social or governance (“ESG”) criteria on a sector-specific basis (“ESG criteria”).

name: Direxion Daily Semiconductor Bull 3X Shares
merged_description: This fund provides aggressive, short-term exposure by seeking daily investment results, before fees and expenses, equivalent to 300% of the performance of the ICE Semiconductor Index. Its underlying index is rules-based, tracking the 30 largest U.S.-listed semiconductor companies—including manufacturers and service/equipment providers—using a modified float-adjusted market-capitalization weighting, which caps the top five constituents at 8% and remaining ones at 4%. The fund achieves its leveraged objective primarily by investing at least 80% of its assets in financial instruments such as swap agreements, index securities, and related ETFs. As a non-diversified product, its 3x leverage is reset daily; consequently, due to compounding effects, returns over holding periods longer than one day may significantly differ from three times the index's cumulative performance.
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowing for investment purposes) in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index and other financial instruments that provide daily leveraged exposure to the index or to ETFs that track the index. The index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that tracks the performance of the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom:
SOXL provides 3x daily exposure to a modified market-cap-weighted index of 30 US-listed semiconductor companies.

SOXL is an aggressive and bullish 1-day bet on a concentrated portfolio of the 30 largest US-listed semiconductor companies, including manufacturers and providers of services or equipment associated with semiconductors. The funds index employs market-cap-weighting, with the weights of the top five securities capped at 8% and the remaining securities at 4%. The index may include ADRs, whose cumulative weight is capped at 10%. To gain exposure to the index, the fund invests in swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index. SOXL rebalances its 3x leverage dailymeaning over the long haul, targeted returns could look significantly different due to compounding effects of this daily rebalance. Prior to August 25, 2021, the fund tracked the PHLX Semiconductor Sector Index.
description_yahoo: The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index, that, in combination, provide 3X daily leveraged exposure to the index, consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that tracks the performance of the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies. The fund is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, of 300% of the daily performance of the ICE Semiconductor Index. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index, that, in combination, provide 3X daily leveraged exposure to the index, consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that tracks the performance of the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Amplify Natural Resources Dividend Income ETF
merged_description: This investment vehicle aims to mirror the performance of an index targeting high-dividend-paying global companies within the natural resources sector. It typically invests at least 80% of its assets in the index's constituents, which include US-listed common stocks and depositary receipts (ADRs) of firms deriving significant revenue from industries such as energy, chemicals, agriculture, metals and mining, paper products, and timber. To qualify for the index, companies must meet specific criteria, including minimum market capitalization and trading liquidity thresholds, possess an indicated annual dividend yield of at least 3%, and cannot be domiciled in Russia. The underlying index employs a dividend-yield weighting methodology, subject to a cap on individual security weights, resulting in a concentrated portfolio typically comprising 40 to 60 holdings that rebalances quarterly. Reflecting its focused strategy, the fund is classified as non-diversified.
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in the securities that comprise the index, which primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts. It will not concentrate its investments (i.e., invest more than 25% of the value of its total assets) in securities of issuers in any one industry or group of industries, except to the extent that the index concentrates in an industry or group of industries. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom: NDIV offers a dividend-skewed take on the natural resources industry. Starting with a broad universe of dividend-paying US-listed equities and ADRs, the index screens for companies that: 1) derive more than 50% of their revenues in one of the following natural resource, commodity-related industries: energy (oil, gas & consumable fuels), chemicals, agriculture, precious and industrial metals and mining, paper products, and timber, 2) have a market-cap of at least $5 billion, 3) have an average daily traded value of at least $2 million over the last six months, and 4) have an indicated dividend yield of at least 3% annually. The index excludes companies domiciled in Russia. All securities that meet the eligibility screens are selected for inclusion and are weighted according to their indicated dividend yield. Single security weights are capped at 5%. The fund typically holds a narrow portfolio of 40 to 60 securities. The index reconstitutes and rebalances quarterly.
description_yahoo: The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets in the securities that comprise the index, which primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts. The index is a gross total return index that seeks to provide investment exposure to dividend-paying equity securities of global companies operating primarily in the following natural resource, commodity-related industries: energy; chemicals; agriculture; precious and industrial metals & mining; paper products; and timber. The fund is non-diversified.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that generally correspond to the price and yield of the EQM Natural Resources Dividend Income Index. The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets in the securities that comprise the index, which primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts. The index is a gross total return index that seeks to provide investment exposure to dividend-paying equity securities of global companies operating primarily in the following natural resource, commodity-related industries: energy; chemicals; agriculture; precious and industrial metals & mining; paper products; and timber. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Invesco S&P SmallCap Consumer Discretionary ETF
merged_description: This investment vehicle aims to replicate the performance of a capped, market-cap-weighted index focused on the U.S. small-cap consumer discretionary sector. It primarily invests at least 90% of its assets in securities drawn from the S&P SmallCap 600 index, specifically targeting companies engaged in providing consumer goods and services sensitive to economic cycles. Such companies include those involved in household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, automobiles and components, computers and electronics, and hotel and restaurant services. The underlying index employs weighting constraints to limit concentration in individual securities and undergoes quarterly rebalancing, thereby offering targeted exposure to consumer cyclical businesses within the small-cap equity space.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. These companies are principally engaged in the business of providing consumer goods and services that are cyclical in nature, including, but not limited to, household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, computers and electronics, automobiles and auto components, and hotel and restaurant services.
description_etfcom:
PSCD tracks a market-cap-weighted index of consumer discretionary firms selected from the S&P SmallCap 600.

PSCD represents the consumer cyclicals segment of the S&P SmallCap 600, a market-cap-weighted index that consists of US small-cap companies screened for size, liquidity, and financial viability. The fund uses GICS in identifying consumer discretionary firms, which may include those engaged in leisure products and services, apparel, luxury goods, automobiles, computers and electronics, and hotel and restaurant services. Selected securities are weighted by market cap and are constrained, such that individual securities will not exceed 22.5% weight and the aggregate weight of securities with over 4.5% allocation is capped at 45% weight of the portfolio. The index rebalances quarterly.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the S&P SmallCap 600® Capped Consumer Discretionary Index (the “underlying index”). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. These companies are principally engaged in the business of providing consumer goods and services that are cyclical in nature, including, but not limited to, household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, computers and electronics, automobiles and auto components, and hotel and restaurant services.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Financials ETF
merged_description: This ETF provides focused exposure to the U.S. financials sector by investing in the common stocks of companies included in the S&P 500® Financials Index, as classified by GICS. It utilizes an equal-weighting strategy, meaning each security in the index is given the same significance in the portfolio, contrasting with traditional market-cap weighting. This approach inherently reduces concentration in the largest financial institutions and amplifies the impact of relatively smaller firms within the S&P 500 universe, offering broader diversification across the sector. The fund generally invests at least 90% of its assets in the securities comprising its underlying index and rebalances quarterly to maintain the equal weighting.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Financials Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the financials sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_etfcom: RSPF offers an equal-weight play on the US financials sector. In contrast to market-cap-weighting, the funds equal-weighting scheme increases the impact of smaller firms in the portfolio at the expense of larger ones, and greatly reduces concentration to top holdings. For RSPF, this smaller-cap tilt is lessened by the fund's S&P 500-restricted universe, which excludes most small-caps. Still, its equal-weighting limits the importance of dominant players in the sector and creates more exposure to less known companies. This can become an advantage when markets are hostile toward big banks. The index is rebalanced on a quarterly basis. Prior to June 07, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker, RYF.
description_yahoo: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Financials Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the financials sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard ("GICS").

name: Breakwave Dry Bulk Shipping ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded product seeks to provide investors exposure to the daily price changes of dry bulk freight futures. It primarily invests in a portfolio tracking a three-month strip of the nearest calendar quarter futures contracts, based on specified indices that measure rates for shipping dry bulk freight like iron ore, coal, and grain. This portfolio comprises futures linked to Capesize (weighted 50%), Panamax (40%), and Supramax (10%) vessel sizes, with weights rebalanced annually. As the first ETP offering direct exposure to freight futures, it accesses a unique market segment instrumental to global commodities and historically uncorrelated with other major asset classes. However, potential investors should be aware that futures provide imperfect spot price tracking, long-term holdings may be subject to decay due to factors like contango, and the product is structured as a commodity pool, which involves K-1 tax reporting.
description_original: The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing substantially all of its assets in the Freight Futures currently constituting the Benchmark Portfolio. The Benchmark Portfolio includes a combination of Capesize, Panamax and Supramax Freight Futures.
description_etfcom:
BDRY tracks an index of long-only exposure to the nearest calendar quarter of dry bulk freight futures contracts on specified indexes.

BDRY is the first ETP to provide exposure to freight futures. Dry bulk shipping is an instrumental part of the global commodity market, and uncorrelated with other major asset classes historically. Dry bulk carrier transport unpackaged dry cargo, such as iron ore, coal, and grain - distinct from tankers and containerized cargo ships. BDRY provides exposure to the charter rate for dry bulk shipping by holding near-dated freight futures contracts on three dry bulk indices. The portfolio uses a fixed weighting scheme, rebalanced annually, based on the cargo ships size category - Capesize freight futures contracts get 50% weight, Panamax contracts 40%, and Supramax contracts 10%. As futures are always an imperfect proxy for spot prices, and the freight futures market is often in contango, long-term holdings are subject to position decay. BDRY is structured as a commodities pool, so expect a K-1 at tax time and long-term holders will be taxed on any gains even without selling shares.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide investors with exposure to the daily change in the price of dry bulk freight futures, before expenses and liabilities of the fund, by tracking the performance of a portfolio consisting of a three-month strip of the nearest calendar quarter of futures contracts on specified indexes that measure rates for shipping dry bulk freight. The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing substantially all of its assets in the Freight Futures currently constituting the Benchmark Portfolio. The Benchmark Portfolio includes a combination of Capesize, Panamax and Supramax Freight Futures.

name: MicroSectors U.S. Big Banks Index 3X Leveraged ETNs
merged_description: This exchange-traded note, structured as senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal, provides three times leveraged exposure to the daily gross total return performance of an equal-weighted index. The underlying index comprises the 10 largest U.S. banking stocks by market capitalization. Returns are compounded daily and are reduced by fees, including a Daily Financing Charge and a Daily Investor Fee, along with potential redemption costs. Due to daily rebalancing and the effects of compounding, this instrument is intended for short-term trading purposes and is not suitable for long-term investment, as its performance over extended periods may significantly differ from three times the cumulative index return.
description_original: The notes are senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal with a return linked to a three times leveraged participation in the performance of the index, compounded daily, less a Daily Investor Fee, the Daily Financing Charge and, if applicable, the Redemption Fee Amount. The index is an equal-dollar weighted index designed to represent the 10 U.S. stocks with the largest market capitalization in the banking sector.
description_etfcom:
BNKU tracks three times the performance of an equal-weighted index of US large banks.

BNKU is a leveraged take on US Big Banks. Specifically, the fund tracks three times the performance of the underlying index, which selects the 10 largest qualifying stocks and evenly weights them. Note, however, that the product isnt designed for long-term investors. The fund rebalances daily. As a result, compounding and path dependency make its long-term returns difficult to predict when compared to its underlying index. BNKU is essentially a relaunch of an old ETN that was available from April 2, 2019, to July 24, 2024, with the same ticker and exposure.
description_yahoo: The ETNs are senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal with a return linked to a three times leveraged participation in the performance of the index, compounded daily, less a Daily Financing Charge, the Daily Investor Fee and, if applicable, the Redemption Fee Amount.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide three times leveraged participation in the gross total return version of the Solactive MicroSectors™ U.S. Big Banks Index. The ETNs are senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal with a return linked to a three times leveraged participation in the performance of the index, compounded daily, less a Daily Financing Charge, the Daily Investor Fee and, if applicable, the Redemption Fee Amount.

name: Cabana Target Leading Sector Aggressive ETF
merged_description: This former fund operated as an actively managed ETF composed of other ETFs, pursuing an aggressive capital growth strategy. It utilized a proprietary algorithm combining fundamental economic data and technical price analysis to guide investments across a broad range of asset classes, including global equities, fixed income, real estate, currencies, and commodities. A key aspect of the strategy involved identifying potentially outperforming sectors based on the current business cycle phase, while also allowing allocation to less correlated assets to manage volatility. The sub-adviser maintained discretionary oversight to override the algorithm if necessary. Characterized as non-diversified, the fund was delisted and concluded trading on January 5, 2024.
description_original: The fund is an actively managed ETF that seeks to achieve its investment objective primarily by allocating its assets among ETFs that invest in securities of companies in the various sectors of the U.S. market: communication services, consumer discretionary, consumer staples, energy, financials, health care, industrials, information technology, materials, real estate, and utilities. It is non-diversified.
description_etfcom: The security was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is January 05, 2024CLSA is an actively-managed fund-of-funds that allocate its exposure based on the economic conditions and market outlook for five very broad asset classes: equities, fixed income, real estate, currencies and commodities. Equities will include both domestic and foreign companies, including emerging markets. Fixed Income securities have no restrictions in terms of maturity, quality or duration. The Sub-Adviser uses a proprietary algorithm that combines fundamental economic and technical price data to identify investments in sectors that appear to be attractive based on the current business cycle. Through the algo, CLSA can also allocate across less-/non-correlated asset classes to manage volatility or any potential market declines. The fund utilizes an aggressive investment style, meaning it will aim for capital growth and maximize its returns. Note that the Sub-Adviser has full discretion to override the algo if a perceived breakdown or systemic change has occurred.

name: First Trust Dorsey Wright Focus 5 ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund employs a concentrated, tactical strategy, investing at least 90% of its assets in just five other First Trust ETFs. These five are selected from a broader universe encompassing First Trust's US sector and global thematic ETFs, chosen based on the Dorsey Wright relative strength model to identify those exhibiting the strongest price momentum and meeting liquidity criteria. The selected ETFs are then held in equal weights within the portfolio. To manage turnover, while relative strength is monitored regularly, constituents are typically only replaced if their momentum falls significantly relative to peers. The underlying ETFs often utilize multi-factor strategies instead of traditional market-cap weighting, potentially leading to a mid-cap focus and offering a distinct, momentum-driven alternative exposure to global equities.
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the exchange-traded funds ("ETFs") that comprise the index. The index is designed to provide targeted exposure to the five First Trust sector-based ETFs that the index provider believes offer the greatest potential to outperform the other ETFs in the selection universe and that satisfy certain trading volume and liquidity requirements.
description_etfcom: FV uses the Dorsey Wright relative strength model to make big bets on US sectors and global themes. The fund holds just 5 ETFsall from First Trustchosen from the issuer's entire stable of broad US sector funds and narrower global niche plays. The 5 ETFs are selected based on relative price momentum. The selected funds are then weighted equally in the portfolio. Note that while the underlying index measures relative strength weekly, an ETF won't drop out until it falls below the median level of relative strength in FV's small universe. This buffer is meant to reduce turnover. The underlying ETFs often use multi-factor exposure rather than cap-weighting, typically overweighting mid-caps. In short, FV looks nothing like a typical plain-vanilla global ETF. Still, the fund rounds out the picture of an accessible alternative exposure to global equities. The index is evaluated on a bi-monthly basis.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an index called the Dorsey Wright Focus Five Index (the "index"). The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the exchange-traded funds ("ETFs") that comprise the index. The index is designed to provide targeted exposure to the five First Trust sector-based ETFs that the index provider believes offer the greatest potential to outperform the other ETFs in the selection universe and that satisfy certain trading volume and liquidity requirements.

name: KraneShares MSCI China ESG Leaders Index ETF
merged_description: This fund invests primarily in Chinese companies selected for high environmental, social, and governance (ESG) ratings compared to industry peers, tracking a corresponding free-float adjusted, market-capitalization-weighted index. Its holdings encompass various publicly issued Chinese share types, including A-shares and those listed internationally. The underlying index employs a multi-stage screening process, evaluating ESG risk management, assessing negative operational impacts based on global frameworks, and excluding firms involved in controversial activities, ultimately selecting constituents to represent 50% of the market cap in each sector while prioritizing higher-rated companies. The fund adheres to specific weighting constraints, limiting single-issuer concentration to 10% and the total weight of large holdings (over 5%) to 40%. Importantly, this fund is closing, with its last trading day set for October 18, 2023.
description_original: Normally, the fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in instruments in its underlying index or in instruments that have economic characteristics similar to those in the underlying index. The underlying index is a free-float adjusted market capitalization weighted index, modified per the 10/40 Constraint, which is designed to measure the equity market performance of Chinese companies that have high ESG ratings relative to their industry peers. It is non-diversified.
description_etfcom:
KESG tracks a market-cap-weighted index of Chinese companies that have high environmental, social and governance ratings.

The fund is closing. The last day of trading on an exchange is October 18, 2023. KESG tracks an index of Chinese stocks with the highest ESG ratings. All types of publicly issued shares of Chinese issuers are eligible, including: A-shares, and those listed in Hong Kong or outside China. Constituents are selected from its parent index, MSCI EM Asia ESG Leaders Index using three screens. First, issuers within each industry are rated on how well they manage ESG risks, Second, an assessment on the negative ESG impact of the firms operations, products and service based on global frameworks such as UN Declaration of Human Rights, and Third, excludes firms involved in controversial activities like civilian firearms and nuclear power. After this initial screening, the index uses the following process to select and rank securities until it covers 50% of the market cap in each sector: 1) eligible securities in the top 35% of market cap, 2) highly-rated securities in the top 50%, 3) current holdings in the top 65%, 4) other eligible securities. At each step, higher rated firms are selected first. Holdings are market-cap-weighted within their respective sector. The UCITS III provides constrains on the weight of any single group entity at 10% of a funds total assets and the sum of the weights of all group entities representing more than 5% of the fund at 40% of the funds total assets.

name: JPMorgan U.S. Tech Leaders ETF
merged_description: This actively managed fund aims for long-term capital appreciation by investing primarily in U.S. equity securities of technology and technology-enabled companies. Its core strategy involves identifying firms believed to be leaders, focusing specifically on those whose future growth potential, in terms of magnitude or duration, appears underestimated by the market. The selection process evaluates companies based on disruptive business models, sustainable competitive advantages, large addressable markets, proven management teams, and financial analysis comparing company performance to consensus expectations. While centered on technology and communication services sectors, the portfolio also includes tech-enabled firms from a wide array of industries that utilize technology to innovate or improve their business, with the potential integration of ESG factors into the investment analysis.
description_original: The fund will invest primarily in equity securities issued by technology and technology-enabled companies which the adviser believes are leaders and where the magnitude and/or duration of future growth for these companies is underappreciated by the market.
description_etfcom: JTEK actively manages a portfolio of potential tech leaders from various industries. The adviser identifies US equities that exhibit disruptive business models, sustainable competitive advantages, large addressable markets, and a proven management team. The fund targets companies with underappreciated growth, assessed by analyzing company revenues, profit margins, and free cash flows against the consensus expectations over time. The fund focuses on the technology and communication services sectors and tech-enabled firms. Tech-enabled firms leverage new technologies to enhance their business. These may include electronics, engineering and construction, transportation, auto manufacturers, auto parts and equipment, entertainment, leisure time, retail, biotechnology, commercial services, healthcare services, pharmaceuticals, diversified financials, insurance, REITs, advertising, media, and energy-alternate sources. The adviser may integrate ESG factors into the selection process.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide long-term capital appreciation. The fund will invest primarily in equity securities issued by technology and technology-enabled companies which the adviser believes are leaders and where the magnitude and/or duration of future growth for these companies is underappreciated by the market.

name: Amplify Online Retail ETF
merged_description: This ETF provides targeted exposure to the global online retail sector, focusing on companies deriving at least 70% of their revenue from online sales. It aims to track an index reflecting this theme, investing primarily in global equity securities, including common stocks, American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), and Global Depositary Receipts (GDRs), intending to capture potential capital appreciation. The portfolio employs a unique methodology, allocating a minimum of 75% to U.S. companies and the remainder to foreign firms, with holdings equally weighted within these two geographic segments. This equal-weighting strategy promotes diversification and prevents concentration in mega-cap names but may introduce a tilt towards smaller, potentially riskier companies; the preference for ADRs/GDRs for foreign exposure, especially in emerging markets, might also influence the investable universe. The underlying index is rebalanced semi-annually.
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in global equity securities that comprise the index, which will primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts, such as ADRs and GDRs. The index seeks to measure the performance of global equity securities of publicly traded companies with significant revenue from the online retail business. The index methodology is designed to result in a portfolio that has the potential for capital appreciation.
description_etfcom:
IBUY tracks an index of global stocks issued by firms with revenues dominated by online retail sales. Stocks are equally weighted within two geographic buckets.

IBUY offers straightforward and diversified equity exposure to global online retailers. The fund holds stock in firms with at least 70% of their revenues from online sales. Firms can be of any market cap subject to typical minimum size and liquidity constraints. US stocks receive a 75% minimum weight, foreign stocks receive the remainder. Stocks are equally weighted within the two geographic buckets. The equal weighting adds diversity and keeps giants like Amazon from dominating the basket, but also introduces a bias to smaller and possibly more risky firms. For foreign coverage, IBUY prefers ADRs and GDRs for developed market exposure and requires these stock substitutes for emerging market names. These constraints may help liquidity but reduce the universe of eligible foreign firms. The index is also rebalanced semi-annually. Overall, IBUYs targeted online coverage and methodology should be considered when investing in this fund.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that generally correspond (before fees and expenses) to the price and yield of the EQM Online Retail Index. The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in global equity securities that comprise the index, which will primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts, such as ADRs and GDRs. The index seeks to measure the performance of global equity securities of publicly traded companies with significant revenue from the online retail business. The index methodology is designed to result in a portfolio that has the potential for capital appreciation.

name: Invesco ESG NASDAQ Next Gen 100 ETF
merged_description: This investment fund provides exposure to the next generation of Nasdaq-listed, non-financial companies by tracking an index that integrates stringent environmental, social, and governance (ESG) criteria. Typically investing at least 90% of its assets in the index components, the fund focuses on the 100 largest domestic and international companies listed on Nasdaq that fall outside the main Nasdaq-100 Index®. Its core strategy involves applying an ESG overlay: companies are initially screened to exclude controversial business activities, followed by assessments to remove firms with high ESG risk scores or significant business controversy levels, while also mandating compliance with UN Global Compact principles. The final constituents are weighted based on a combination of their ESG risk ratings and market capitalization, with the index rebalancing quarterly. Investors should note that the fund is classified as non-diversified.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of companies included in the Nasdaq Next Generation 100 Index® (the “parent index”) that also meet the index provider's ESG criteria. The parent index is comprised of securities of the next generation of Nasdaq-listed non-financial companies. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom:
QQJG tracks an index of NASDAQ Next Gen 100 stocks screened and weighted based on various environmental, social, and governance factors.

QQJG provides exposure to NASDAQ Next Gen 100 stocks utilizing an ESG overlay. Eligible securities comprise the next generation domestic and international, non-financial companies listed on NASDAQthat is the largest 100 companies outside of the NASDAQ-100 Index. The fund initially screens out companies involved in controversial business activities, as determined by Sustainalytics. Firms ESG profiles are then assessed using corporate filings and public disclosures to remove companies with high business controversy levels and high ESG Risk Rating Scores. Companies must also comply with the principles of the UN Global Compact. Remaining securities are selected for inclusion and are weighted according to a combination of their ESG Risk Rating Scores and market capitalizations. The index rebalances and reconstitutes quarterly. QQJG adds an ESG offering to Invesco's QQQ Innovation Suite.
description_yahoo: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of companies included in the Nasdaq Next Generation 100 Index® (the “parent index”) that also meet the index provider's ESG criteria. The parent index is comprised of securities of the next generation of Nasdaq-listed non-financial companies.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the Nasdaq Next Generation 100 ESG Index®. The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of companies included in the Nasdaq Next Generation 100 Index® (the “parent index”) that also meet the index provider's ESG criteria. The parent index is comprised of securities of the next generation of Nasdaq-listed non-financial companies.

name: Xtrackers Municipal Infrastructure Revenue Bond ETF
merged_description: This investment vehicle seeks to track the performance of an index composed of tax-exempt, investment-grade municipal securities. It specifically targets long-term revenue bonds, with maturities of at least ten years, issued to finance infrastructure projects by state and local entities. The fund invests overwhelmingly (at least 80% of assets) in these types of bonds, deliberately excluding general obligation issues backed by taxing power. This exclusive focus on long-duration infrastructure revenue bonds results in potentially heightened interest rate and credit risk compared to the broader municipal bond market, and may lead to significant portfolio concentration in certain states.
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets (but typically far more) in instruments that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is comprised of tax-exempt municipal securities issued by states, cities, counties, districts, their respective agencies, and other tax-exempt issuers.
description_etfcom:
RVNU tracks an index of investment-grade muni bonds backed by revenue from infrastructure projects. Constituents have at least 10 years remaining to maturity.

RVNU exclusively targets long-term infrastructure revenue bonds, a narrow slice of the muni bond space. As such, the fund avoids all general obligation issues, which are backed by the taxing power of its issuers, and only holds bonds tied to revenues from specific infrastructure projects. This has the dual effect of increasing the fund`s interest rate and credit risk exposure relative to the broad muni market. None of RVNU's bonds mature in less than ten years. Investors should be conscious of the funds portfolio, as some states like Texas, New York and Massachusetts might make up a sizeable portion of it.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the performance, before fees and expenses, of the Solactive Municipal Infrastructure Revenue Bond Index (the "underlying index"). The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets (but typically far more) in instruments that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is comprised of tax-exempt municipal securities issued by states, cities, counties, districts, their respective agencies, and other tax-exempt issuers.

name: iShares MSCI Global Impact ETF
merged_description: This investment vehicle targets global companies whose business models are fundamentally aligned with advancing the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). It primarily invests in firms deriving at least 50% of their revenue from products and services addressing key social and environmental challenges, while explicitly screening out those significantly involved (over 10% of sales) in alcohol, tobacco, or predatory lending. The fund aims to track an underlying index reflecting this theme, typically committing at least 80% of its assets to index components spanning developed and emerging markets across all capitalization sizes. This index maintains a minimum of 30 holdings, applies issuer (4%) and sector (20%) caps, and weights constituents annually based on the proportion of impact-related revenue, scaled by overall company revenue, leading to a focused portfolio potentially distinct from broad market benchmarks.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index is composed of companies that derive a majority of their revenue from products and services that address at least one of the world's major social and environmental challenges as identified by the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
description_etfcom:
SDG tracks an index composed of companies whose revenues are driven by products and services that address at least one of the United Nation's Sustainable Development Goals.

SDG tracks an ESG-focused index composed of global companies that derive at least 50% of their revenues from products and services that further the United Nation's Sustainable Development Goals. Companies are explicitly deselected if more than 10% of sales are from alcohol, tobacco, or are involved in predatory lending. The index must contain at least 30 issuers, with an issuer cap of 4% and a sector cap of 20%. Constituent weight is based on the percent of income derived from the above-stated impact sales, scaled by trailing 12-month revenues and rebalanced annually. Given the fund's narrow construction and loose constraints, the fund could vary considerably from cap-weighted exposure and performance, and may not be comparable with broad-based indices. The fund can invest in both developed and emerging markets, with allowances for all market caps. SDG traded under the ticker MPCT until Oct. 24, 2018. There was no change to the fund's index or strategy.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the performance of the MSCI ACWI Sustainable Development Index. The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index is composed of companies that derive a majority of their revenue from products and services that address at least one of the world's major social and environmental challenges as identified by the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.

name: Motley Fool 100 Index ETF
merged_description: This non-diversified fund seeks to replicate the performance of a proprietary, rules-based index established in 2017, focusing on U.S. companies endorsed by the index provider's research. Specifically, the index comprises the 100 largest and most liquid U.S. companies drawn from recommendations within the provider's various newsletters and its highest-rated stocks according to internal analyst opinions. These selected companies are market-capitalization weighted, and the index, which excludes certain securities like ADRs and preferred stock, is reconstituted quarterly. Under normal market conditions, the fund invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities that make up this index.
description_original: Under normal circumstances, at least 80% of the fund's total assets (exclusive of any collateral held from securities lending) will be invested in the component securities of the index. The index was established by TMF in 2017 and is a proprietary, rules-based index designed to track the performance of the 100 largest, most liquid U.S. companies that have been recommended by TMF’s analysts and newsletters. The fund is non-diversified.
description_etfcom: TMFC tracks an index of US stocks, selected by Motley Fool analysts, which are recommended in Motley Fool research newsletters, such as Stock Advisor and Rule Breakers. The index also includes the 150 top-rated stocks in the Motley Fool IQ analyst opinion database. Each publication follows a distinct research strategy that targets specific areas of the market, such as small-cap or penny stocks, dividend-paying stocks, or value stocks. From this selection pool, the index chooses the 100 largest US companies by market cap and weights them according to market capitalization. The following securities are excluded: ADRs, GDR, EDRs, preferred stocks, closed-end funds, exchange-traded funds and derivatives. The index undergoes quarterly reconstitution.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond (before fees and expenses) generally to the total return performance of the Motley Fool 100 Index. Under normal circumstances, at least 80% of the fund's total assets (exclusive of any collateral held from securities lending) will be invested in the component securities of the index. The index was established by TMF in 2017 and is a proprietary, rules-based index designed to track the performance of the 100 largest, most liquid U.S. companies that have been recommended by TMF’s analysts and newsletters. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Invesco DWA Technology Momentum ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund tracks a specialized index targeting technology sector companies demonstrating strong relative strength or price momentum. It generally invests at least 90% of its assets in the index components, which consist of a minimum of 30 securities selected and weighted based on these momentum characteristics. Employing a full replication strategy, the fund's composition can differ markedly from traditional market-cap-weighted technology exposures, potentially leading to significant sector bets, holdings outside the conventional tech sphere, and a focus on companies with lower average market capitalizations, consequently carrying elevated risk. The portfolio is reconstituted and rebalanced on a quarterly basis.
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of at least 30 securities of companies in the technology sector that have powerful relative strength or "momentum" characteristics.
description_etfcom:
PTF tracks an index of U.S. tech firms selected and weighted by price momentum.

PTF continues to provide an alternate take on US technology firms following a 2014 index change. The fund now follows a Dorsey-Wright relative strength index that selects and weights stocks by price momentum in an effort to outperform the broad market. This momentum-based take can swing the fund far from neutral exposure, with major sector bets and even sizeable allocations outside the traditional tech sphere. The fund carries a much lower average market cap compared to the broad market, and attendant risk is elevated as a result. The fund selects the top, at least 30 stocks, with the highest momentum scores in the technology space. The fund uses a full replication indexing strategy. Investors should consider all-in costs of holding the fund. The fund is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. Prior to August 28, 2023, the ETF's name was Invesco DWA Technology Momentum ETF.
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the Dorsey Wright Technology Technical LeadersTMIndex (the "underlying index"). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of at least 30 securities of companies in the technology sector that have powerful relative strength or "momentum" characteristics.

name: SPDR S&P Health Care Equipment ETF
merged_description: This exchange-traded fund aims to reflect the performance of an index focused on the U.S. health care equipment and supplies sub-industries, derived from the broader S&P Total Market Index. Utilizing a sampling strategy, it invests substantially all, typically at least 80%, of its assets in securities comprising this index, which is rebalanced quarterly. The fund employs an equal-weighting approach across its holdings, providing exposure to large, mid, and small-cap companies but often resulting in a significant small-cap tilt relative to the broader market. This methodology offers investors highly targeted, potentially less concentrated exposure within this specific niche, serving as an alternative to broader healthcare funds often dominated by large pharmaceutical and service companies.
description_original: The SPDRS&PHealth Care Equipment ETF seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of S&PHealth Care Equipment Select Industry Index (the “Index”)Seeks to provide exposure to the health care equipment segment of the S&P TMI, which comprises the following sub-industries: Health Care Equipment and Health Care SuppliesSeeks to track a modified equal weighted index which provides the potential for unconcentrated industry exposure across large, mid and small cap stocksAllows investors to take strategic or tactical positions at a more targeted level than traditional sector based investing
description_etfcom:
XHE tracks an equal-weighted index of U.S. health care equipment and supplies companies.

XHE offers equal-weight exposure to US companies in the health care equipment & supplies business. While XHE's holdings encompass all cap sizes, its weighted average market cap is only a fraction of the market's, giving it a significant small-cap tilt. XHE is not for everyone--it targets an extremely narrow market. Yet, XHE provides an alternative play for healthcare investors aiming to avoid the heavy hand of big pharma and service providers that dominate the broader industry. The index is rebalanced quarterly.
description_yahoo: In seeking to track the performance of the S&P Health Care Equipment Select Industry Index (the "index"), the fund employs a sampling strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index represents the health care equipment segment of the S&P Total Market Index ("S&P TMI").
description_morningstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of an index derived from the health care equipment and supplies segment of a U.S. total market composite index. In seeking to track the performance of the S&P Health Care Equipment Select Industry Index (the "index"), the fund employs a sampling strategy.
